## Diagnosis

The core issue is a **coordinate-system mismatch** between where you measure and where you render.

ScrollSpy active labels and hover labels are siblings in the DOM but they resolve their positions differently:

- **Hover labels** are positioned relative to the **rail's own stacking context** — they use the rail as their offset parent, so `right: 100%` or a negative `translateX` naturally places them in the left gutter.
- **Active label** is anchored to a **tick element** (or now the notch container), but if that element is `position: static` or is inside a `fixed`/`absolute` subtree whose offset parent is the **viewport** rather than the rail, `right: 100%` resolves against the wrong containing block — the viewport — and the label flies to the far right or off-screen.

Switching the anchor from tick → notch container didn't help because **both elements share the same broken containing block chain**. The real root cause is that the active label's CSS `position` context is never the rail.

**Root cause — AP-072 (Escaped Containing Block):** The active label's offset parent resolves to the viewport (or document body) instead of the rail, because no ancestor in the active-label's render path has `position: relative/absolute/fixed` with a narrower scope than the viewport.

Secondary cause: The label is likely rendered via a **React portal or a top-level overlay div** outside the rail's DOM subtree, so even a correct `position: relative` on the notch won't help.

---

## Root Cause Chain

```
<ScrollSpyRail>          ← position: fixed, right: 0  (correct offset parent for hover labels)
  <NotchContainer>       ← position: relative  (you tried anchoring here — still inside rail ✓)
    <Tick />             ← position: absolute
  <HoverLabel />         ← rendered here, right:100% works ✓

<ActiveLabel />          ← rendered HERE, outside <ScrollSpyRail> subtree
                            → offset parent = viewport
                            → right:100% = viewport-width − label-width → far right ✗
```

---

## Fix

### 1. Move `ActiveLabel` into the rail's DOM subtree

The label must be a descendant of (or a sibling inside) the element that has `position: fixed` / `position: relative` as its containing block.

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyRail.tsx`**

```tsx
// BEFORE — active label rendered outside, e.g. in a portal or at page root
// AFTER — render it as a direct child of the rail

export function ScrollSpyRail({ items, activeId }: ScrollSpyRailProps) {
  return (
    <nav
      className={styles.rail}   // position: fixed; right: 0; top: 0; bottom: 0
      aria-label="Page sections"
    >
      {/* ── Active label lives INSIDE the rail, same containing block as hover labels ── */}
      <ActiveSectionLabel
        items={items}
        activeId={activeId}
      />

      {items.map((item) => (
        <ScrollSpyItem key={item.id} item={item} isActive={item.id === activeId} />
      ))}
    </nav>
  )
}
```

---

### 2. Fix the active label's CSS to match the hover-label anchor pattern

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpy.module.css`** (or your Tailwind classes)

```css
/* ── Hover labels (existing — DO NOT change) ── */
.hoverLabel {
  position: absolute;
  right: 100%;          /* flush to left edge of rail */
  top: 50%;
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  white-space: nowrap;
  pointer-events: none;
}

/* ── Active label — must mirror the hover label's containing-block assumptions ── */
.activeLabel {
  position: absolute;   /* ← NOT fixed, NOT static */
  right: 100%;          /* same anchor: left edge of rail */
  /* 
    Vertical position: interpolate toward the active item's notch.
    Use a CSS custom property set inline by the JS/React side.
  */
  top: var(--active-label-top, 50%);
  transform: translateY(-50%);
  white-space: nowrap;
  transition: top 300ms cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);

  /* Visually differentiate from hover labels */
  font-weight: 600;
  opacity: 1;
}
```

---

### 3. Drive `--active-label-top` from the active notch's position

**`components/ScrollSpy/ActiveSectionLabel.tsx`**

```tsx
'use client'

import { useEffect, useRef, useState } from 'react'
import styles from './ScrollSpy.module.css'

interface Props {
  items: { id: string; label: string }[]
  activeId: string | null
}

export function ActiveSectionLabel({ items, activeId }: Props) {
  const railRef = useRef<HTMLElement | null>(null)
  const [topPct, setTopPct] = useState<string>('50%')

  useEffect(() => {
    // Walk up from this component's root to find the rail (its position:fixed parent)
    // OR: accept a railRef prop from ScrollSpyRail for precision
    if (!activeId) return

    const notch = document.querySelector(
      `[data-scrollspy-id="${activeId}"] .${styles.notch}`
    ) as HTMLElement | null

    const rail = notch?.closest('[data-scrollspy-rail]') as HTMLElement | null

    if (!notch || !rail) return

    const railRect = rail.getBoundingClientRect()
    const notchRect = notch.getBoundingClientRect()

    // Top relative to the rail's own coordinate space
    const relativeTop = notchRect.top - railRect.top + notchRect.height / 2
    setTopPct(`${relativeTop}px`)
  }, [activeId])

  const activeItem = items.find((i) => i.id === activeId)
  if (!activeItem) return null

  return (
    <span
      className={styles.activeLabel}
      style={{ '--active-label-top': topPct } as React.CSSProperties}
      aria-current="true"
    >
      {activeItem.label}
    </span>
  )
}
```

Add `data-scrollspy-rail` to the rail nav and `data-scrollspy-id` to each item wrapper so the selector above resolves correctly:

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyRail.tsx`** (additions)

```tsx
<nav
  className={styles.rail}
  data-scrollspy-rail          // ← add this
  aria-label="Page sections"
>
```

**`components/ScrollSpy/ScrollSpyItem.tsx`** (additions)

```tsx
<div
  className={styles.item}
  data-scrollspy-id={item.id}  // ← add this
>
```

---

### 4. Verify the rail itself is the containing block

The rail must have a non-`static` position so it becomes the offset parent for all `position: absolute` children:

```css
.rail {
  position: fixed;   /* ✓ this is a containing block for absolute children */
  right: 0;
  top: 0;
  bottom: 0;
  width: var(--rail-width, 1.5rem);
  /* NO transform, NO will-change: transform on ancestors above this — 
     those would promote it to a new stacking context and break fixed positioning */
}
```

> ⚠️ If any ancestor of `.rail` has `transform`, `will-change: transform`, `filter`, or `perspective`, `position: fixed` stops being viewport-fixed and the coordinate math breaks again (AP-072 secondary vector).

---

## Principle

**A positioned element's `right: 100%` resolves against its nearest non-static ancestor — not the element you intuitively think of as its "parent" in the UI.** Always verify the containing-block chain in DevTools (`Computed → Containing Block`) before changing the anchor element. Moving the anchor within the same broken subtree produces no change; you must either (a) move the element into the correct subtree, or (b) change the CSS `position` of an ancestor to establish the right containing block. Portal-rendered overlays are the most common source of this class of bug.
